      "updated": 1776315421727,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "React reconciliation is the process React uses to **update the DOM efficiently** when your app’s state or props change.\n\nInstead of reloading the whole page, React compares the **old Virtual DOM** with the **new Virtual DOM** and updates only what actually changed.\n\n---\n\n## 🧠 Core Idea (in simple terms)\n\nThink of it like this:\n\n* You change some data (state/props)\n* React creates a **new Virtual DOM tree**\n* It compares it with the **previous Virtual DOM**\n* It finds differences (**diffing**)\n* It updates only those parts in the real DOM\n\nThis whole process is called **Reconciliation**.\n\n---\n\n## 🔄 Step-by-Step Process\n\n### 1. State/Props Change\n\nWhenever data changes:\n\n```js\nsetCount(count + 1);\n```\n\n---\n\n### 2. New Virtual DOM Created\n\nReact builds a new tree of elements in memory.\n\n---\n\n### 3. Diffing Algorithm Runs\n\nReact compares:\n\n* Old Virtual DOM\n* New Virtual DOM\n\nThis is called **diffing**.\n\n---\n\n### 4. Minimal Updates to Real DOM\n\nReact updates only what changed, not everything.\n\n---\n\n## ⚡ Diffing Rules (Very Important)\n\nReact uses some smart assumptions to make it fast:\n\n### 1. Different element types → Replace completely\n\n```jsx\n<div> → <p>\n```\n\n➡️ React destroys old and creates new\n\n---\n\n### 2. Same type → Update only changed attributes\n\n```jsx\n<div className=\"red\"> → <div className=\"blue\">\n```\n\n➡️ Only class changes, not whole element\n\n---\n\n### 3. Lists use keys (VERY IMPORTANT)\n\n```jsx\n{items.map(item => <li key={item.id}>{item.name}</li>)}\n```\n\nKeys help React:\n\n* Identify which items changed\n* Avoid unnecessary re-renders\n\nWithout keys → React gets confused → poor performance\n\n---\n\n## 📊 Example\n\n```jsx\n// Old\n<ul>\n  <li>A</li>\n  <li>B</li>\n</ul>\n\n// New\n<ul>\n  <li>A</li>\n  <li>C</li>\n</ul>\n```\n\n➡️ React updates only **B → C**, not the whole list\n\n---\n\n## ⚠️ Why Keys Matter\n\nBad:\n\n```jsx\n<li key={index}>\n```\n\nGood:\n\n```jsx\n<li key={item.id}>\n```\n\nBecause:\n\n* Index changes → React re-renders unnecessarily\n* Unique IDs → stable updates\n\n---\n\n## 🚀 Why Reconciliation is Important\n\n* Improves performance\n* Avoids full page reloads\n* Makes React apps fast and efficient\n\n---\n\n## 🧩 Virtual DOM vs Real DOM\n\n| Feature      | Virtual DOM | Real DOM  |\n| ------------ | ----------- | --------- |\n| Speed        | Fast        | Slow      |\n| Updates      | Batched     | Immediate |\n| Manipulation | Cheap       | Expensive |\n\n---\n\n## 🧠 One-Line Summary\n\n**Reconciliation = React’s smart way of comparing old and new UI and updating only what changed.**\n\n---\n\nIf you want, I can show you:\n\n* 🔍 How reconciliation works internally with Fiber\n* ⚡ Interview questions on this topic\n* 🧪 Coding examples where bad keys break UI\n",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "React reconciliation is the process React uses to **update the DOM efficiently** when your app’s state or props change.\n\nInstead of reloading the whole page, React compares the **old Virtual DOM** with the **new Virtual DOM** and updates only what actually changed.\n\n---\n\n## 🧠 Core Idea (in simple terms)\n\nThink of it like this:\n\n* You change some data (state/props)\n* React creates a **new Virtual DOM tree**\n* It compares it with the **previous Virtual DOM**\n* It finds differences (**diffing**)\n* It updates only those parts in the real DOM\n\nThis whole process is called **Reconciliation**.\n\n---\n\n## 🔄 Step-by-Step Process\n\n### 1. State/Props Change\n\nWhenever data changes:\n\n```js\nsetCount(count + 1);\n```\n\n---\n\n### 2. New Virtual DOM Created\n\nReact builds a new tree of elements in memory.\n\n---\n\n### 3. Diffing Algorithm Runs\n\nReact compares:\n\n* Old Virtual DOM\n* New Virtual DOM\n\nThis is called **diffing**.\n\n---\n\n### 4. Minimal Updates to Real DOM\n\nReact updates only what changed, not everything.\n\n---\n\n## ⚡ Diffing Rules (Very Important)\n\nReact uses some smart assumptions to make it fast:\n\n### 1. Different element types → Replace completely\n\n```jsx\n<div> → <p>\n```\n\n➡️ React destroys old and creates new\n\n---\n\n### 2. Same type → Update only changed attributes\n\n```jsx\n<div className=\"red\"> → <div className=\"blue\">\n```\n\n➡️ Only class changes, not whole element\n\n---\n\n### 3. Lists use keys (VERY IMPORTANT)\n\n```jsx\n{items.map(item => <li key={item.id}>{item.name}</li>)}\n```\n\nKeys help React:\n\n* Identify which items changed\n* Avoid unnecessary re-renders\n\nWithout keys → React gets confused → poor performance\n\n---\n\n## 📊 Example\n\n```jsx\n// Old\n<ul>\n  <li>A</li>\n  <li>B</li>\n</ul>\n\n// New\n<ul>\n  <li>A</li>\n  <li>C</li>\n</ul>\n```\n\n➡️ React updates only **B → C**, not the whole list\n\n---\n\n## ⚠️ Why Keys Matter\n\nBad:\n\n```jsx\n<li key={index}>\n```\n\nGood:\n\n```jsx\n<li key={item.id}>\n```\n\nBecause:\n\n* Index changes → React re-renders unnecessarily\n* Unique IDs → stable updates\n\n---\n\n## 🚀 Why Reconciliation is Important\n\n* Improves performance\n* Avoids full page reloads\n* Makes React apps fast and efficient\n\n---\n\n## 🧩 Virtual DOM vs Real DOM\n\n| Feature      | Virtual DOM | Real DOM  |\n| ------------ | ----------- | --------- |\n| Speed        | Fast        | Slow      |\n| Updates      | Batched     | Immediate |\n| Manipulation | Cheap       | Expensive |\n\n---\n\n## 🧠 One-Line Summary\n\n**Reconciliation = React’s smart way of comparing old and new UI and updating only what changed.**\n\n---\n\nIf you want, I can show you:\n\n* 🔍 How reconciliation works internally with Fiber\n* ⚡ Interview questions on this topic\n* 🧪 Coding examples where bad keys break UI\n",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
